 Latency Analysis](#A7 \"In Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n    1. [G.1 Kernel Implementations and Fusion Structure](#A7.SS1 \"In Appendix G Inference Kernel Latency Analysis ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n    2. [G.2 Extended Prefill and Prefill+Decode Latency Measurements](#A7.SS2 \"In Appendix G Inference Kernel Latency Analysis ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n       1. [Models.](#A7.SS2.SSS0.Px1 \"In G.2 Extended Prefill and Prefill+Decode Latency Measurements ‣ Appendix G Inference Kernel Latency Analysis ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n       2. [Setting.](#A7.SS2.SSS0.Px2 \"In G.2 Extended Prefill and Prefill+Decode Latency Measurements ‣ Appendix G Inference Kernel Latency Analysis ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n \n\n[License: CC BY 4.0](https://info.arxiv.org/help/license/index.html#licenses-available) \n\narXiv:2603.15569v1 [cs.LG] 16 Mar 2026\n\n# Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\n\nAakash Lahoti Equal contribution.    Kevin Y. Li 11footnotemark: 1     Berlin Chen 11footnotemark: 1     Caitlin Wang 11footnotemark: 1     Aviv Bick     J. Zico Kolter        \nTri Dao Equal advising.    Albert Gu22footnotemark: 2\n\n###### Abstract\n\nScaling inference-time compute has emerged as an important driver of LLM performance, making inference efficiency a central focus of model design alongside model quality. While the current Transformer-based models deliver strong model quality, their quadratic compute and linear memory make inference expensive. This has spurred the development of sub-quadratic models with reduced linear compute and constant memory requirements. However, many recent linear models trade off model quality and capability for algorithmic efficiency, failing on tasks such as state tracking. Moreover, their theoretically linear inference remains hardware-inefficient in practice. Guided by an inference-first perspective, we introduce three core methodological improvements inspired by the state space model (SSM) viewpoint of linear models. We combine: (1) a more expressive recurrence derived from SSM discretization, (2) a complex-valued state update rule that enables richer state tracking, and (3) a multi-input, multi-output (MIMO) formulation for better model performance without increasing decode latency. Together with architectural refinements, our Mamba-3 model achieves significant gains across retrieval, state-tracking, and downstream language modeling tasks. At the 1.5B scale, Mamba-3 improves average downstream accuracy by 0.6 percentage points compared to the next best model (Gated DeltaNet), with Mamba-3’s MIMO variant further improving accuracy by another 1.2 points for a total 1.8 point gain. Across state-size experiments, Mamba-3 achieves comparable perplexity to Mamba-2 despite using half of its predecessor’s state size. Our evaluations demonstrate Mamba-3’s ability to advance the performance-efficiency Pareto frontier.\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nTest-time compute has emerged as a key driver of progress in LLMs, with techniques like chain-of-thought reasoning and iterative refinement demonstrating that inference-time scaling can unlock new capabilities [wu2025inferencescalinglawsempirical, snell2024scalingllmtesttimecompute]. The rapid rise of parallel, agentic workflows has only intensified the need for efficient inference and deployment of such models [openai\\_gpt53\\_codex\\_2026, anthropic\\_claude\\_opus\\_46\\_2026]. This paradigm shift makes inference efficiency [kwon2023efficientmemorymanagementlarge, li2024llminferenceservingsurvey] paramount, as the practical impact of AI systems now depends critically on their ability to perform large-scale inference during deployment. Model architecture design plays a fundamental role in determining inference efficiency, as architectural choices directly dictate the computational and memory requirements during generation. While Transformer-based models [vaswani2017attention] are the current industry standard, they are fundamentally bottlenecked by linearly increasing memory demands through the KV cache and quadratically increasing compute requirements through the self-attention mechanism. These drawbacks have motivated recent lines of work on sub-quadratic models, e.g., state space models (SSMs) and linear attention, which retain constant memory and linear compute while attaining comparable or better performance than their Transformer counterparts. These models have made it into the mainstream, with layers such as Mamba-2 [dao2024transformersssmsgeneralizedmodels] and Gated DeltaNet (GDN) [schlag2021deltarule, yang2025parallelizinglineartransformersdelta] recently incorporated into large-scale hybrid models that match the performance of pure Transformer alternatives with much higher efficiency [nvidia2025nemotronhfamilyaccurateefficient, qwen3technicalreport, kimiteam2025kimilinearexpressiveefficient, tencenthunyuanteam2025hunyuanturbosadvancinglargelanguage].\n\nDespite the success of linear models, significant progress remains in improving their performance, in particular on advancing the Pareto frontier between model quality and inference efficiency. For example, Mamba-2 was developed to improve training speed and simplicity over Mamba-1 [gu2024mambalineartimesequencemodeling], by sacrificing some expressivity and thus performing worse for inference-matched models. In addition, they have been shown to lack certain capabilities, such as poor state-tracking abilities, e.g., simply determining parity of bit sequences [grazzi2025unlockingstatetrackinglinearrnns, sarrof2024expressivecapacitystatespace]. Finally, despite these sub-quadratic models being prized for theoretically efficient inference and thus their widespread adoption, their inference algorithms are not hardware efficient. In particular, because these algorithms were developed from a training perspective, their decoding phase has low arithmetic intensity (the ratio of FLOPs to memory traffic), resulting in large portions of hardware remaining idle.\n\nTo develop more performant models from an inference-first paradigm, we introduce three core methodological changes on top of Mamba-2, influenced by an SSM-centric viewpoint of sub-quadratic models.\n\n##### Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization.\n\nWe provide a simple technique for discretizing time-varying, selective SSMs. Through our framework, we can derive several new discretization methods. One of our instantiations, referred to as “exponential-Euler,” formalizes Mamba-1 and Mamba-2’s heuristic discretization that previously lacked theoretical justification. Our new “exponential-trapezoidal” instantiation is a more expressive generalization of “exponential-Euler,” where the recurrence can be expanded to reveal an implicit convolution applied on the SSM input. Combined with explicit B,CB,C bias terms, Mamba-3 can empirically replace the short causal convolution in language model architectures, which was previously hypothesized to be essential for recurrent models.\n\n##### Complex-valued State Space Model.\n\nBy viewing the underlying SSM of Mamba-3 as complex-valued, we enable a more expressive state update than Mamba-2’s. This change in update rule, designed to be lightweight for training and inference, overcomes the lack of state-tracking ability common in many current linear models. We show that our complex-valued update rule is equivalent to a data-dependent rotary embedding and can be efficiently computed [su2023roformerenhancedtransformerrotary], and empirically demonstrate its ability to solve synthetic tasks outside the capabilities of prior linear models.\n\n##### Multi-Input, Multi-Output (MIMO) SSM.\n\nTo improve FLOP efficiency during decoding, we switch from an outer-product–based state update to a matrix-multiplication–based state update. From the view of the signal processing foundations of SSMs, such a transition exactly coincides with the generalization from a single-input single-output (SISO) sequence dynamics to a multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) one. Here, we find that MIMO is particularly suitable for inference, as the extra expressivity enables more computation during the memory-bound state update during decoding, without increasing the state size and compromising speed.\n\nPut together, these improvements form the core of our Mamba-3 layer. Methodologically, we note that these all arise naturally from an SSM-centric perspective but are not immediate from other popular viewpoints of modern linear layers such as linear attention or test-time regression; we discuss these connections further in [Section˜5](#S5 \"5 Related Work ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"). Empirically, we validate our new model’s abilities and capabilities on a suite of synthetic state-tracking and language-modeling tasks.\n\n* •\n\n  Better Quality. At 1.5B scale, Mamba-3 (MIMO) improves downstream language modeling accuracy by +2.2 over Transformers, +1.9 points over Mamba-2, and +1.8 over GDN, while Mamba-3 (SISO) improves over the next best model, GDN, by +0.6 points. Furthermore, across state size experiments, Mamba-3 (MIMO) with state size 64 matches the perplexity of Mamba-2 with state size 128, effectively achieving the same language modeling performance with half the latency.\n* •\n\n  New Capabilities. Mamba-3’s complexification of the SSM state enables it to solve synthetic state-tracking tasks that Mamba-2 cannot. We empirically demonstrate that the efficient RoPE-like calculation is able to near perfectly solve arithmetic tasks, while Mamba-3 without RoPE and Mamba-2 perform no better than random guessing.\n* •\n\n  Inference Efficiency. Mamba-3 (MIMO) improves hardware utilization. It increases decoding FLOPs by up to 4×\\times relative to Mamba-2 at fixed state size, while maintaining similar wall-clock decode latency, and simultaneously improving perplexity and downstream performance. We release fast training and inference kernels for Mamba-3.111<https://github.com/state-spaces/mamba>.\n\nMamba-3 (SISO) improves quality and capability over prior linear models, and Mamba-3 (MIMO) further improves performance over Mamba-3 (SISO) and other strong baselines while matching inference speed with Mamba-2. Both of our Mamba-3 variants advance the performance-latency Pareto frontier through their strong modeling capabilities and hardware-efficient design.\n\n## 2 Preliminaries\n\n### 2.1 Notation\n\nScalars are denoted by plain-text letters (e.g., x,yx,y). Tensors, including vectors and matrices, are denoted by bold letters (e.g., 𝒉,𝑪{\\bm{h}},{\\bm{C}}). The shape of the tensor can be inferred from the context. We denote the input sequence length as TT, the model dimension as DD, and the SSM state size as NN. For time indices, we use subscripts (e.g., xtx\\_{t} for the input at time tt). The Hadamard product between two tensors is denoted by ⊙\\odot. For a vector 𝒗∈ℝd{\\bm{v}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d}, we denote Diag​(𝒗)∈ℝd×d\\mathrm{Diag}({\\bm{v}})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d\\times d} as the diagonal matrix with the vector 𝒗{\\bm{v}} as the diagonal, and for products of scalars across time steps, we use the notation αt​⋯​s=αt:s×=∏i=stαi\\alpha\\_{t\\cdots s}=\\alpha^{\\times}\\_{t:s}=\\prod\\_{i=s}^{t}\\alpha\\_{i}.\n\n### 2.2 SSM Preliminaries\n\nState Space Models (SSMs) describe continuous-time linear dynamics via\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉˙​(t)\\displaystyle\\dot{{\\bm{h}}}(t) | =𝑨​(t)​𝒉​(t)+𝑩​(t)​x​(t),\\displaystyle={\\bm{A}}(t)\\,{\\bm{h}}(t)+{\\bm{B}}(t)\\,x(t), | y​(t)\\displaystyle y(t) | =𝑪​(t)⊤​𝒉​(t),\\displaystyle={\\bm{C}}(t)^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}(t), |\n\nwhere 𝒉​(t)∈ℝN{\\bm{h}}(t)\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{N} is the hidden state, x​(t)∈ℝx(t)\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R} the input, and 𝑨​(t)∈ℝN×N{\\bm{A}}(t)\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times N}, 𝑩​(t),𝑪​(t)∈ℝN{\\bm{B}}(t),{\\bm{C}}(t)\\!\\in\\!\\mathbb{R}^{N}. We will occasionally refer to 𝑨​(t){\\bm{A}}(t) as the *state-transition* and 𝑩​(t)​x​(t){\\bm{B}}(t)x(t) as the *state-input*; this also extends to their discretized counterparts. For discrete sequences with step size Δt\\Delta\\_{t}, Mamba-1 and Mamba-2 *discretized* the system to the following recurrence\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | =eΔt​𝑨t​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​xt,\\displaystyle=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{A}}\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\,x\\_{t}, | yt\\displaystyle y\\_{t} | =𝑪t⊤​𝒉t.\\displaystyle={\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}. |\n\n##### Mamba-2’s Parameterization.\n\nThe core of the Mamba-2 layer [dao2024transformersssmsgeneralizedmodels] is a *data-dependent* and hardware-efficient SSM. Both the state-transition and state-input are made data-dependent through the projection of Δt∈ℝ>0\\Delta\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}\\_{>0} and 𝑩,𝑪∈ℝN{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N} from the current token. By parameterizing the state-transition 𝑨t{\\bm{A}}\\_{t} as a scalar times identity (𝑨t=At​𝑰N×N{\\bm{A}}\\_{t}=A\\_{t}\\bm{I}\\_{N\\times N}, where At∈ℝ<0A\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}\\_{<0}), the SSM recurrence can be efficiently computed with the matrix multiplication tensor cores of GPUs. Defining αt≔eΔt​At∈(0,1)\\alpha\\_{t}\\coloneqq e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\in(0,1) and γt≔Δt\\gamma\\_{t}\\coloneqq\\Delta\\_{t}, the update becomes\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t=αt​𝒉t−1+γt​𝑩t​xt,yt=𝑪t⊤​𝒉t.{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=\\alpha\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\gamma\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\,x\\_{t},\\qquad y\\_{t}={\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}. | (1) |\n\nThe data-dependent state-transition αt\\alpha\\_{t} controls the memory horizon of each SSM within the layer. Δt\\Delta\\_{t} in particular modulates both the state-transition and state-input: a larger Δt\\Delta\\_{t} forgets faster and up-weights the current token more strongly, while a smaller Δt\\Delta\\_{t} retains the hidden state with minimal contributions from the current token.\n\n###### Remark 1.\n\nIn Mamba-2, AtA\\_{t} is data-independent, since the overall discrete transition αt≔eΔt​At\\alpha\\_{t}\\coloneqq e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}} is data-dependent through Δt\\Delta\\_{t}. In Mamba-3, we empirically found that data-dependent AtA\\_{t} has similar performance to data-independent AtA\\_{t}, and chose the former as a default for consistency so that all SSM parameters are data-dependent.\n\n### 2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality\n\nMamba-2 showed that a large class of SSMs admit a *matrix* form that vectorizes the time-step recurrence. Through the state space duality (SSD) framework, recurrent SSMs can be represented within a parallel form that incorporates an element-wise mask to model the state-transition decay.\n\nSSD provides a general framework for a duality between linear recurrence and parallelizable (matrix-multiplication-based) computational forms\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒀=(𝑳⊙𝑪​𝑩⊤)​𝑿\\displaystyle{\\bm{Y}}=({\\bm{L}}\\odot{\\bm{C}}{{\\bm{B}}}^{\\top}){\\bm{X}} | (2) |\n\nwhere 𝑳∈ℝT×T{\\bm{L}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times T} is a structured mask, 𝑩,𝑪∈ℝT×N{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times N}, 𝑿∈ℝT×D{\\bm{X}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times D} are the inputs to the SSM and 𝒀∈ℝT×D{\\bm{Y}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times D} is its output. Different structures on 𝑳{\\bm{L}} give rise to various instantiations of SSD.\n\nEquation ([2](#S2.E2 \"Equation 2 ‣ 2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) also draws a general connection between recurrence and attention, by setting 𝑸≔𝑪{\\bm{Q}}\\coloneqq{\\bm{C}}, 𝑲≔𝑩{\\bm{K}}\\coloneqq{\\bm{B}}, 𝑽≔𝑿{\\bm{V}}\\coloneqq{\\bm{X}} and viewing 𝑳{\\bm{L}} as a data-dependent mask. In fact, the simplest case of SSD is (causal) linear attention [linearattention], where 𝑳{\\bm{L}} is the causal triangular mask.\n\nMamba-2 is a generalization where\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝑳=[1α11⋮⋱αT​…​1⋯αT1]⋅Diag(γ)\\displaystyle{\\bm{L}}=\\begin{bmatrix}1\\\\ \\alpha\\_{1}&1\\\\ \\vdots&&\\ddots\\\\ \\alpha\\_{T...1}&\\cdots&\\alpha\\_{T}&1\\end{bmatrix}\\cdot\\operatorname\\*{Diag}(\\gamma) | (3) |\n\ncomposed of terms αt,γt\\alpha\\_{t},\\gamma\\_{t} from equation ([1](#S2.E1 \"Equation 1 ‣ Mamba-2’s Parameterization. ‣ 2.2 SSM Preliminaries ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).222In the original Mamba-2 paper, γ\\gamma does not appear because it is viewed as folded into the 𝑩{\\bm{B}} term. In this paper, 𝑩t{\\bm{B}}\\_{t} represents the continuous parameter, whereas in Mamba-2, 𝑩t{\\bm{B}}\\_{t} represents the discretized parameter which is equivalent to γt​𝑩t\\gamma\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}.\n\nIn [Section˜3.1.3](#S3.SS1.SSS3 \"3.1.3 Parallel Representation of Exponential-Trapezoidal Recurrence ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), we show that Mamba-3 is a generalization of Mamba-2 with a more expressive 𝑳{\\bm{L}}, and hence also an instance of SSD.\n\n## 3 Methodology\n\nWe introduce Mamba-3, a state space model with three new innovations: “exponential-trapezoidal” discretization for more expressive dynamics ([Section˜3.1](#S3.SS1 \"3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), complex-valued state spaces for state tracking ([Section˜3.2](#S3.SS2 \"3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), and multi-input multi-output (MIMO) to improve modeling power and inference-time hardware utilization ([Section˜3.3](#S3.SS3 \"3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). These advances address the quality, capability, and efficiency limitations of current sub-quadratic architectures. We combine these together into an updated Mamba architecture block in [Section˜3.4](#S3.SS4 \"3.4 Mamba-3 Architecture ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\n### 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization\n\nStructured SSMs are naturally defined as continuous-time dynamical systems that map input functions, x​(t)∈ℝx(t)\\in\\mathbb{R}, to output functions, y​(t)∈ℝy(t)\\in\\mathbb{R}, for time t>0t>0. The underlying continuous state space system is defined by a first-order ordinary differential equation (ODE) for the state 𝒉˙​(t)\\dot{{\\bm{h}}}(t) and an algebraic equation for the output y​(t)y(t). In sequence modeling, however, the data is only observed at discrete time steps, which then requires applying a *discretization step* to the SSM to transform its continuous-time dynamics into a discrete recurrence.\n\n![Refer to caption](2603.15569v1/x1.png) \n\nFigure 1: Left: The structured mask induced by the exponential-trapezoidal rule ([Section˜3.1](#S3.SS1 \"3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) is a product of the decay and two-band convolutional mask. Right: Euler (hold endpoint) versus Trapezoidal (average endpoints) integral approximation.\n\n   \n\nTable 1:  Table of canonical linear-time invariant discretizations (top) and custom linear-time varying discretizations derived from our exponential-adjusted framework (bottom), along with their appearance in structured SSMs used in deep learning. Our theory formalizes the prior Mamba discretization as exponential-Euler and extends it with the more expressive exponential-trapezoidal method. The generalized discretization framework converts a continuous SSM 𝒉​(t)˙=𝑨​(t)​𝒉​(t)+𝑩​(t)​x​(t)\\dot{{\\bm{h}}(t)}={\\bm{A}}(t){\\bm{h}}(t)+{\\bm{B}}(t)x(t) into the discrete recurrence 𝒉t=αt​𝒉t−1+βt​𝑩t−1​xt−1+γt​𝑩t​xt{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\beta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t-1}x\\_{t-1}+\\gamma\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, where various discretization methods yield different formulas for αt,βt,γt\\alpha\\_{t},\\beta\\_{t},\\gamma\\_{t}.\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Discretization Method | αt\\alpha\\_{t} | βt\\beta\\_{t} | γt\\gamma\\_{t} | Appearance |\n| Forward Euler | I+Δ​AI+\\Delta A | — | Δ\\Delta | — |\n| Backward Euler | (I−Δ​A)−1(I-\\Delta A)^{-1} | — | (I−Δ​A)−1​Δ(I-\\Delta A)^{-1}\\,\\Delta | — |\n| Trapezoidal | (I−Δ2​A)−1​(I+Δ2​A)(I-\\frac{\\Delta}{2}A)^{-1}\\,(I+\\frac{\\Delta}{2}A) | — | (I−Δ2​A)−1​Δ(I-\\frac{\\Delta}{2}A)^{-1}\\,\\Delta | S4 |\n| Zero-Order Hold | exp⁡(Δ​A)\\exp({\\Delta A}) | — | A−1​(exp⁡(Δ​A)−I)A^{-1}\\,\\left(\\exp({\\Delta A})-I\\right) | |  | | --- | | S4D, S5 | |\n| Zero-Order Hold | exp⁡(Δt​At)\\exp({\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}) | — | At−1​(exp⁡(Δt​At)−I)A\\_{t}^{-1}\\,\\left(\\exp({\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}})-I\\right) |\n| Exponential-Euler | exp⁡(Δt​At)\\exp({\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}) | — | Δt\\Delta\\_{t} | Mamba-1, -2333While the Mamba-1 paper reports ZOH discretization, the implementation follows <https://github.com/state-spaces/mamba/issues/129>. |\n| Exponential-Trapezoidal | exp⁡(Δt​At)\\exp({\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}) | (1−λt)​Δt​exp⁡(Δt​At)(1-\\lambda\\_{t})\\Delta\\_{t}\\,\\exp({\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}) | λt​Δt\\lambda\\_{t}\\,\\Delta\\_{t} | Mamba-3 |\n\nDiscretization methods are well-studied in classical control theory with several canonical formulas used in earlier SSM works in deep learning [S4, S4D, S5]. These mechanisms were traditionally stated and applied to linear-time invariant (LTI) systems, and their derivations do not directly apply to linear-time varying (LTV) systems. Additionally, while Mamba-1 adapted the zero-order hold (ZOH) method to LTV systems without proof, the complexity associated with selective SSMs prompted the use of an additional heuristic approximation that lacked theoretical justification and did not correspond to any established discretization technique. In the following subsection, we formalize the previous heuristics used in current LTV SSMs through our discretization framework and utilize it to propose a more expressive discretization scheme.\n\n#### 3.1.1 Overview of Exponential-Adjusted Discretization\n\nWe introduce a simple derivation that leads to a class of new discretization methods for LTV state space models. The method can be instantiated in various ways; we show that one instantiation results in the heuristic used in Mamba-1/2, thereby theoretically justifying it (exponential-Euler). We also introduce a more powerful discretization (exponential-trapezoidal) used in Mamba-3.\n\nThe high-level intuition of our derivation originates from the closed form solution x​(t)=et​A​x​(0)x(t)=e^{tA}x(0) of a simple linear ODE x′​(t)=A​x​(t)x^{\\prime}(t)=Ax(t), which discretizes to xt+1=eΔ​A​xtx\\_{t+1}=e^{\\Delta A}x\\_{t}. In this example, the exponential dominates the dynamics of the underlying first-order ODE, resulting in imprecise approximations when using low-order methods without significantly constraining Δ\\Delta. Thus, we analyze the dynamics of the *exponential-adjusted* system e−A​t​x​(t)e^{-At}x(t). The adjusted system yields a discrete recurrent form where the state-transition and the state-input integrals are approximated separately—the state-transition integral is approximated by a right-hand approximation, i.e. A​(s)≔A​(τt)A(s)\\coloneqq A(\\tau\\_{t}) for all s∈[τt−1,τt]s\\in[\\tau\\_{t-1},\\tau\\_{t}], yielding,\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉​(τt)\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}(\\tau\\_{t}) | =exp⁡(∫τt−1τtA​(s)​𝑑s)​𝒉​(τt−1)⏟via right-hand approximation+∫τt−1τtexp⁡(∫ττtA​(s)​𝑑s)​𝑩​(τ)​x​(τ)​𝑑τ⏟via different discretization schemes,\\displaystyle=\\underbrace{\\exp\\left(\\int\\_{\\tau\\_{t-1}}^{\\tau\\_{t}}A(s)ds\\right){\\bm{h}}(\\tau\\_{t-1})}\\_{\\text{via right-hand approximation}}+\\underbrace{\\int\\_{\\tau\\_{t-1}}^{\\tau\\_{t}}\\exp\\left(\\int\\_{\\tau}^{\\tau\\_{t}}A(s)ds\\right){\\bm{B}}(\\tau)x(\\tau)d\\tau}\\_{\\text{via different discretization schemes}}, |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | ≈exp⁡(Δt​At)​𝒉t−1+∫τt−1τtexp⁡((τt−τ)​At)​𝑩​(τ)​x​(τ)​𝑑τ,\\displaystyle\\approx\\exp\\left(\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}\\right){\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\int\\_{\\tau\\_{t-1}}^{\\tau\\_{t}}\\exp\\left((\\tau\\_{t}-\\tau)A\\_{t}\\right){\\bm{B}}(\\tau)x(\\tau)d\\tau, |\n\nwhich serves as the foundation for further discretization techniques for the state-input integral. The full derivation is detailed in [Appendix˜A](#A1 \"Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\n##### ZOH.\n\nThe classical zero-order hold discretization method can be derived from the foundation above with a specific approximation of the right-hand side integral. By treating At,𝑩​(τ),x​(τ)A\\_{t},{\\bm{B}}(\\tau),x(\\tau) as constants over the interval [τt−1,τt][\\tau\\_{t-1},\\tau\\_{t}] where the values are fixed to the right endpoint τt\\tau\\_{t}, the integral results in At−1​(exp⁡(Δt​At)−I)​𝑩t​xtA\\_{t}^{-1}\\,\\left(\\exp(\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t})-I\\right){\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}.\n\nWe note that this formally proves that the classical ZOH formula for LTI systems applies to LTV by naively replacing the parameters A,B,ΔA,B,\\Delta with their time-varying ones.\n\n##### Exponential-Euler (Mamba-1/-2).\n\nWhile Mamba-1 stated to use the time-varying ZOH formula above, Mamba-1 and Mamba-2 actually used an additional approximation in the released implementation. This discretization can be recovered by approximating the state-input integral with *Euler’s rule* [Süli\\_Mayers\\_2003] and holding the (right) endpoint constant throughout the interval (Fig. [1](#S3.F1 \"Figure 1 ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"))\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\; | ≈eΔt​At​𝒉t−1+(τt−τt−1)​e(τt−τt)​At​𝑩t​xt\\displaystyle\\approx\\;e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;(\\tau\\_{t}-\\tau\\_{t-1})e^{(\\tau\\_{t}-\\tau\\_{t})A\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\,x\\_{t} |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| =eΔt​At​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​xt.\\displaystyle=\\;e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;\\Delta\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\,x\\_{t}. | (4) |\n\nWe call equation ([4](#S3.E4 \"Equation 4 ‣ Exponential-Euler (Mamba-1/-2). ‣ 3.1.1 Overview of Exponential-Adjusted Discretization ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) the *exponential-Euler* discretization method, stemming from the exponential integration followed by Euler approximation. This derivation justifies the formulas used in Mamba-1/-2’s implementation.\n\n##### Exponential-Trapezoidal (Mamba-3).\n\nHowever, Euler’s rule provides only a first-order approximation of the state-input integral and its local truncation error scales as O​(Δt2)O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{2}). In contrast, we introduce a *generalized trapezoidal rule*, which provides a second-order accurate approximation of the integral, offering improved accuracy over Euler’s rule. Specifically, it approximates the integral with a *data-dependent, convex combination of both interval endpoints*. This generalization extends the classical trapezoidal rule [Süli\\_Mayers\\_2003], which simply averages the interval endpoints ([Figure˜1](#S3.F1 \"In 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).\n\n{restatable}\n\n[Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization]propositionPropTrap Approximating the state-input integral in equation ([16](#A1.E16 \"Equation 16 ‣ Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) by the general trapezoidal rule yields the recurrence,\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\; | =eΔt​At​𝒉t−1+(1−λt)​Δt​eΔt​At​𝑩t−1​xt−1+λt​Δt​𝑩t​xt,\\displaystyle=\\;e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;(1-\\lambda\\_{t})\\Delta\\_{t}e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t-1}x\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;\\lambda\\_{t}\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, | (5) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| ≕αt​𝒉t−1+βt​𝑩t−1​xt−1+γt​𝑩t​xt,\\displaystyle\\eqqcolon\\;\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;\\beta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t-1}x\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;\\gamma\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, | (6) |\n\nwhere λt∈[0,1]\\lambda\\_{t}\\in[0,1] is a data-dependent scalar, αt≔eΔt​At\\alpha\\_{t}\\coloneqq e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}, βt≔(1−λt)​Δt​eΔt​At\\beta\\_{t}\\coloneqq(1-\\lambda\\_{t})\\Delta\\_{t}e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}, γt≔λt​Δt\\gamma\\_{t}\\coloneqq\\lambda\\_{t}\\Delta\\_{t}.\n\n###### Remark 2 (Expressivity).\n\nThe exponential-trapezoidal rule is a generalization of (a) the classical trapezoid rule, which is recovered when λt=12\\lambda\\_{t}=\\tfrac{1}{2}, and (b) Mamba-2’s Euler’s rule, which is recovered when λt=1\\lambda\\_{t}=1.\n\n###### Remark 3 (Error Rate).\n\nThis is a second-order discretization of the state-input integral and its error scales as O​(Δt3)O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}) under standard stability assumptions, provided that the trapezoidal parameter satisfies λt=12+O​(Δt)\\lambda\\_{t}=\\tfrac{1}{2}+O(\\Delta\\_{t}). However, our ablations indicate that not enforcing this constraint is better for empirical performance. See Appendix [A.2](#A1.SS2 \"A.2 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization Error Rate ‣ Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") and [A.3](#A1.SS3 \"A.3 Exponential-Trapezoidal Parameterization ‣ Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") for details.\n\nOur new discretization framework and the two instantiations, exponential-Euler and exponential-trapezoidal, are, to the best of our knowledge, novel for structured SSMs used in deep learning. [Table˜1](#S3.T1 \"In 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") compares and summarizes canonical and commonly used discretization schemes for state space models.\n\n#### 3.1.2 Exponential-Trapezoidal Recurrence as an Implicit Convolution\n\nOur generalized exponential-trapezoidal discretization is equivalent to applying a *data-dependent* convolution of size two on the state-input to the SSM. In particular, a normal SSM in recurrent form materializes the state-input 𝒗t=𝑩t​xt{\\bm{v}}\\_{t}={\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, then computes a linear recurrence 𝒉t=αt​𝒉t−1+γt​𝒗t{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\gamma\\_{t}{\\bm{v}}\\_{t}. In equation ([6](#S3.E6 \"Equation 6 ‣ Exponential-Trapezoidal (Mamba-3). ‣ 3.1.1 Overview of Exponential-Adjusted Discretization ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) we instead first apply a width-2 convolution on 𝒗t{\\bm{v}}\\_{t} (weighted by β,γ\\beta,\\gamma) before passing it into the linear recurrence.\n\n###### Remark 4 (Convolution Differences).\n\nThere is a distinct difference between the “convolution” induced by exponential-trapezoidal discretization and the standard short convolutions used by sequence models such as Mamba and GDN. Standard short convolutions are independent operations applied on xtx\\_{t} (and often 𝑩t,𝑪t{\\bm{B}}\\_{t},{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}) outside the core recurrence, while our new discretization can be interpreted as a convolution on the *state-input* 𝑩t​xt{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t} *within* the core recurrence.\n\n#### 3.1.3 Parallel Representation of Exponential-Trapezoidal Recurrence\n\nOur new recurrence can be instantiated as a case of SSD and has a corresponding parallel form to equation ([2](#S2.E2 \"Equation 2 ‣ 2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). Expanding the state recurrence from 𝒉0=γ0​𝑩0​x0{\\bm{h}}\\_{0}=\\gamma\\_{0}{\\bm{B}}\\_{0}x\\_{0} results in 𝒉T=αT​⋯​2​(γ0​α1+β1)​𝑩0​x0+⋯+γT​𝑩T​xT{\\bm{h}}\\_{T}=\\alpha\\_{T\\cdots 2}(\\gamma\\_{0}\\alpha\\_{1}+\\beta\\_{1}){\\bm{B}}\\_{0}x\\_{0}+\\cdots+\\gamma\\_{T}{\\bm{B}}\\_{T}x\\_{T}, where the SSM output is 𝒚T=αT​⋯​2​(γ0​α1+β1)​𝑪T⊤​𝑩0​x0+⋯+γT​𝑪T⊤​𝑩T​xT{\\bm{y}}\\_{T}=\\alpha\\_{T\\cdots 2}(\\gamma\\_{0}\\alpha\\_{1}+\\beta\\_{1}){\\bm{C}}\\_{T}^{\\top}{\\bm{B}}\\_{0}x\\_{0}+\\cdots+\\gamma\\_{T}{\\bm{C}}\\_{T}^{\\top}{\\bm{B}}\\_{T}x\\_{T}. Unrolling these rows shows that the mask induced by the trapezoidal update is no longer a fixed averaging of endpoints (as in the classical trapezoid rule), but a *data-dependent convex combination* of the two interval endpoints.\n\nUnder the SSD framework ([2](#S2.E2 \"Equation 2 ‣ 2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) with parallel form 𝒀=(𝑳⊙𝑪​𝑩⊤)​𝑿{\\bm{Y}}=({\\bm{L}}\\odot{\\bm{C}}{{\\bm{B}}}^{\\top}){\\bm{X}}, Mamba-3 corresponds to a mask 𝑳{\\bm{L}} whose structure is a 1-semiseparable matrix composed with a 2-band matrix:444Incidentally, this is a special case of a 2-semiseparable matrix.\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝑳=[γ0(γ0​α1+β1)γ1α2​(γ0​α1+β1)(γ1​α2+β2)γ2⋮⋱αT​⋯​2​(γ0​α1+β1)⋯γT]=[1α11α2​α1α21⋮⋱αT​⋯​1⋯1]​[γ0β1γ10β2γ2⋮⋱0⋯γT].\\displaystyle{\\bm{L}}=\\begin{bmatrix}\\gamma\\_{0}&&&\\\\ (\\gamma\\_{0}\\alpha\\_{1}+\\beta\\_{1})&\\gamma\\_{1}&&\\\\ \\alpha\\_{2}(\\gamma\\_{0}\\alpha\\_{1}+\\beta\\_{1})&(\\gamma\\_{1}\\alpha\\_{2}+\\beta\\_{2})&\\gamma\\_{2}&\\\\ \\vdots&&&\\ddots\\\\ \\alpha\\_{T\\cdots 2}(\\gamma\\_{0}\\alpha\\_{1}+\\beta\\_{1})&&&\\cdots&\\gamma\\_{T}\\end{bmatrix}=\\begin{bmatrix}1&&&\\\\ \\alpha\\_{1}&1&&\\\\ \\alpha\\_{2}\\alpha\\_{1}&\\alpha\\_{2}&1&\\\\ \\vdots&&&\\ddots\\\\ \\alpha\\_{T\\cdots 1}&&&\\cdots&1\\end{bmatrix}\\begin{bmatrix}\\gamma\\_{0}&&&\\\\ \\beta\\_{1}&\\gamma\\_{1}&&\\\\ 0&\\beta\\_{2}&\\gamma\\_{2}&\\\\ \\vdots&&&\\ddots\\\\ 0&&&\\cdots&\\gamma\\_{T}\\end{bmatrix}. | (7) |\n\nThis parallel formulation enables the hardware-efficient matmul-focused calculation of the SSM output for training.\n\nWe note that the convolutional connection of Mamba-3 can also be seen through this parallel dual form, where multiplication by the 2-band matrix in equation ([7](#S3.E7 \"Equation 7 ‣ 3.1.3 Parallel Representation of Exponential-Trapezoidal Recurrence ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) represents convolution with weights β,γ\\beta,\\gamma. In [Section˜A.1](#A1.SS1 \"A.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization’s Mask Matrix ‣ Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), we use the SSD tensor contraction machinery to prove that the parallel form is equivalent to a vanilla SSM with a state-input convolution.\n\n###### Remark 5.\n\nThe structured mask of Mamba-3 can be viewed as generalizing Mamba-2, which instead of the 2-band matrix has a diagonal matrix with γt\\gamma\\_{t} only ([3](#S2.E3 \"Equation 3 ‣ 2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).\n\n### 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs\n\nModern SSMs are designed with efficiency as the central goal, motivated by the need to scale to larger models and longer sequences. For instance, successive architectures have progressively simplified the state-transition matrix: S4 [S4] used complex-valued Normal Plus Low Rank (NPLR) matrices, Mamba [gu2024mambalineartimesequencemodeling] reduced this to a diagonal of reals, and Mamba-2 [dao2024transformersssmsgeneralizedmodels] further simplified it to a single scaled identity matrix. Although these simplifications largely maintain language modeling performance, recent works [merrill2025illusionstatestatespacemodels, sarrof2024expressivecapacitystatespace, grazzi2025unlockingstatetrackinglinearrnns] have shown that the restriction to real, non-negative eigenvalue transitions degrades the capabilities of the model on simple state-tracking tasks—here referring primarily to the solvable-group regime (TC0\\text{TC}^{0}) such as parity—which can be solved by a one-layer LSTM. This limitation, formalized in Theorem 1 of [grazzi2024mambacapableincontextlearning], arises from restricting the eigenvalues of the transition matrix to real numbers, which cannot represent “rotational” hidden state dynamics. For instance, consider the parity function on binary inputs {0,1}\\{0,1\\}, defined as ∑txtmod2\\sum\\_{t}x\\_{t}\\bmod 2. This task can be performed using update: 𝒉t=𝑹​(π​xt)​𝒉t−1{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}={\\bm{R}}(\\pi x\\_{t}){\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}, where 𝑹​(⋅){\\bm{R}}(\\cdot) is a 2-D rotation matrix. Such rotational dynamics cannot be expressed with real eigenvalues.\n\n#### 3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization\n\nTo recover this capability, we begin with complex SSMs ([8](#S3.E8 \"Equation 8 ‣ 3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), which *are* capable of representing state-tracking dynamics. We show that, under discretization ([Appendix˜A](#A1 \"Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), complex SSMs can be formulated as real SSMs with a *block-diagonal transition matrix composed of 2×22\\times 2 rotation matrices* ([Section˜3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). We then show that this is equivalent to applying *data-dependent rotary embeddings* on both the input and output projections 𝑩,𝑪{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}} respectively. This result establishes a theoretical connection between complex SSMs and data-dependent RoPE embeddings ([Section˜3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). Finally, the “RoPE trick” used in [su2023roformerenhancedtransformerrotary] allows for an efficient implementation of complex-valued state-transition matrices with minimal computational overhead compared to real-valued SSMs.\n\n{restatable}\n\n[Complex-to-Real SSM Equivalence]propositionPropComplexRealSSM Consider a complex-valued SSM\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉˙​(t)\\displaystyle\\dot{{\\bm{h}}}(t) | =Diag​(A​(t)+i​𝜽​(t))​𝒉​(t)+(𝑩​(t)+i​𝑩^​(t))​x​(t),\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Diag}\\big(A(t)+i\\bm{\\theta}(t)\\big)\\,{\\bm{h}}(t)+\\big({\\bm{B}}(t)+i\\hat{{\\bm{B}}}(t)\\big)\\,x(t), | (8) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| y​(t)\\displaystyle y(t) | =Re​((𝑪​(t)+i​𝑪^​(t))⊤​𝒉​(t)),\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Re}\\!\\left(\\big({\\bm{C}}(t)+i\\hat{{\\bm{C}}}(t)\\big)^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}(t)\\right), |\n\nwhere 𝒉​(t)∈ℂN/2{\\bm{h}}(t)\\in\\mathbb{C}^{N/2}, 𝜽​(t),𝑩​(t),𝑩^​(t),𝑪​(t),𝑪^​(t)∈ℝN/2\\bm{\\theta}(t),{\\bm{B}}(t),\\hat{{\\bm{B}}}(t),{\\bm{C}}(t),\\hat{{\\bm{C}}}(t)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N/2}, and x​(t),A​(t)∈ℝx(t),A(t)\\in\\mathbb{R}. Under exponential-Euler discretization, this system is equivalent to a real-valued SSM\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | =eΔt​At​𝑹t​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​xt,\\displaystyle=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{R}}\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, | (9) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| yt\\displaystyle y\\_{t} | =𝑪t⊤​𝒉t,\\displaystyle={\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}, |\n\nwith state 𝒉t∈ℝN{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N}, projections\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| 𝑩t≔[𝑩t𝑩^t]∈ℝN,𝑪t≔[𝑪t−𝑪^t]∈ℝN,{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\coloneqq\\begin{bmatrix}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\\\ \\hat{{\\bm{B}}}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N},\\qquad{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\coloneqq\\begin{bmatrix}{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\\\ -\\hat{{\\bm{C}}}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N}, |\n\nand a transition matrix\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| 𝑹t≔Block​({R​(Δt​𝜽𝒕​[i])}i=1N/2)∈ℝN×N,R​(θ)≔[cos⁡(θ)−sin⁡(θ)sin⁡(θ)cos⁡(θ)].{\\bm{R}}\\_{t}\\;\\coloneqq\\;\\text{Block}\\Big(\\{R(\\Delta\\_{t}\\bm{\\theta\\_{t}}[i])\\}\\_{i=1}^{N/2}\\Big)\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times N},\\qquad R(\\theta)\\coloneqq\\begin{bmatrix}\\cos(\\theta)&-\\sin(\\theta)\\\\ \\sin(\\theta)&\\cos(\\theta)\\end{bmatrix}. |\n\nThe proof is given in [Section˜B.1](#A2.SS1 \"B.1 Proof of Proposition 3.2.1 ‣ Appendix B Complex SSM Proofs ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\n[Section˜3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") shows that the discretized complex SSM of state dimension N/2N/2 has an equivalent real SSM with doubled state dimension (NN), and its transition matrix is a scalar decayed block-diagonal matrix of 2×22\\times 2 data-dependent rotation matrices (eΔt​At​𝑹te^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}{\\bm{R}}\\_{t}).\n\n{restatable}\n\n[Complex SSM, Data-Dependent RoPE Equivalence]propositionPropRoPETrick Under the notation established in [Section˜3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), consider the real SSM defined in equation ([9](#S3.E9 \"Equation 9 ‣ 3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) unrolled for TT time-steps. The output of the above SSM is equivalent to that of a vanilla scalar transition matrix-based SSM ([4](#S3.E4 \"Equation 4 ‣ Exponential-Euler (Mamba-1/-2). ‣ 3.1.1 Overview of Exponential-Adjusted Discretization ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) with a data-dependent rotary embedding applied on the 𝑩,𝑪{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}} components of the SSM, as defined by:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t=eΔt​At​𝒉t−1+(∏i=0t𝑹i⊤)​Δt​𝑩t​xt,yt=[(∏i=0t𝑹i⊤)​𝑪t]⊤​𝒉t{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\left(\\prod\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}^{\\top}\\_{i}\\right)\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t},\\qquad\\qquad y\\_{t}=\\left[\\left(\\prod\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}^{\\top}\\_{i}\\right){\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\right]^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\qquad | (10) |\n\nwhere the matrix product represents right matrix multiplication, e.g., ∏i=01𝑹i=𝑹0​𝑹1\\prod\\_{i=0}^{1}{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}={\\bm{R}}\\_{0}{\\bm{R}}\\_{1}. We refer to the usage of a transformed real-valued SSM to compute the complex SSM as the “RoPE trick.” The proof is given in [Section˜B.2](#A2.SS2 \"B.2 Proof of Proposition 3.2.1 ‣ Appendix B Complex SSM Proofs ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nTo observe the connection of complex SSMs to RoPE embeddings, note that in the above proposition, the data-dependent rotations 𝑹i{\\bm{R}}\\_{i} are aggregated across time-steps and applied to 𝑪,𝑩{\\bm{C}},{\\bm{B}}, which, by the state space duality framework, correspond to the query (𝑸{\\bm{Q}}) and key (𝑲{\\bm{K}}) components of attention ([Section˜2.3](#S2.SS3 \"2.3 Structured Masked Representation and State Space Duality ‣ 2 Preliminaries ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). Analogously, vanilla RoPE [su2023roformerenhancedtransformerrotary] applies *data-independent* rotation matrices, where the rotation angles follow a fixed frequency schedule 𝜽​[i]=10000−2​i/N\\bm{\\theta}[i]=10000^{-2i/N}.\n\n#### 3.2.2 Complex SSM with Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization\n\nAfter deriving the recurrence for complex SSMs with exponential-Euler discretization, the generalization to exponential-trapezoidal discretization is similar. [Section˜3.2.2](#S3.SS2.SSS2 \"3.2.2 Complex SSM with Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") provides the full recurrence with the RoPE trick for Mamba-3.\n\n{restatable}\n\n[Rotary Embedding Equivalence with Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization]propositionPropRoPETrickTrap\n\nDiscretizing a complex SSM with the exponential-trapezoidal rule ([Section˜3.1.1](#S3.SS1.SSS1.Px3 \"Exponential-Trapezoidal (Mamba-3). ‣ 3.1.1 Overview of Exponential-Adjusted Discretization ‣ 3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) yields the recurrence\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | =αt​𝒉t−1+βt​(∏i=0t−1𝑹i⊤)​𝑩t−1​xt−1+γt​(∏i=0t𝑹i⊤)​𝑩t​xt,\\displaystyle=\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\beta\\_{t}\\left(\\prod\\_{i=0}^{t-1}{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}^{\\top}\\right){\\bm{B}}\\_{t-1}x\\_{t-1}+\\gamma\\_{t}\\left(\\prod\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}^{\\top}\\right){\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t}, |\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| yt\\displaystyle y\\_{t} | =[(∏i=0t𝑹i⊤)​𝑪t]⊤​𝒉t.\\displaystyle=\\left[\\left(\\prod\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}^{\\top}\\right){\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\right]^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}. | (11) |\n\nHere, 𝑹t{\\bm{R}}\\_{t} is the block-diagonal rotation matrix defined in [Section˜3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nThe proof is in [Section˜B.3](#A2.SS3 \"B.3 Proof of Proposition 3.2.2 ‣ Appendix B Complex SSM Proofs ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nWe empirically validate that our complex SSM, implemented via data-dependent RoPE, is capable of solving state-tracking tasks that real-valued SSMs with and without standard RoPE cannot ([Table˜5(b)](#S4.T5.st2 \"In Table 5 ‣ 4.2 SSM Methodology Ablations ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), supporting theoretical claims.\n\n### 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output\n\nScaling test-time compute has opened new frontiers in model capability, such as agentic workflows, where inference takes up an increasing share of the overall compute budget. This has placed a renewed focus on inference efficiency of language models and spurred the adoption of SSMs and sub-quadratic layers which feature fixed-sized hidden states and thus offer lower compute and memory requirements. Although these new layers have a lower wall-clock time compared to Transformers, their decoding is heavily memory-bound, resulting in low hardware utilization. In this section, we use the SSM perspective to introduce a methodological refinement to the Mamba-3 recurrence that allows for *increased model FLOPs without increasing decoding wall-clock time, resulting in a better model with the same decoding speed.*\n\n##### Decoding Arithmetic Intensity.\n\nTo improve hardware efficiency, we need to consider the arithmetic intensity of token generation, defined as FLOPs divided by the number of input-output bytes for a given op. Since SSM decoding saturates the memory bandwidth with idle compute (i.e., being memory-bound), we would like to increase its arithmetic intensity to effectively overlay compute with memory I/O. More concretely, the arithmetic intensity for a single generation in Mamba is around 2.52.5 ops per byte ([Table˜2(a)](#S3.T2.st1 \"In Table 2 ‣ Decoding Arithmetic Intensity. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), while the arithmetic intensity for bfloat16 matmul is about 295295 ops per byte for NVIDIA H100-SXM5 [nvidia\\_h100\\_2022]. Consequently, SSM decoding falls far short of a compute-bound regime, and moreover it is not clear how one can adjust the existing parameters in Mamba to mitigate the lack of hardware efficiency. We note that this observation applies generally to other sub-quadratic models, such as causal linear attention.\n\n \n\nTable 2:  Arithmetic Intensity for (a) SISO, (b) MIMO. The batch and head dimensions cancel out. The arithmetic intensity of MIMO increases linearly with rank RR, enabling better hardware utilization during memory-bound phases like decode. Here NN is the state size (expansion factor) and PP is the head dimension. For Mamba-3, typically R≪N,PR\\ll N,P.\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Input | Output | FLOPs | Arithmetic Intensity |\n| Ht:(N,P)H\\_{t}:(N,P)  xt:(P)x\\_{t}:(P)  at:(1)a\\_{t}:(1)  bt:(N)b\\_{t}:(N)  ct:(N)c\\_{t}:(N) | yt:(P)y\\_{t}:(P) | 5​N​P−P5NP-P | 5​N​P−P2​(1+2​N+P+N​P)\\displaystyle\\frac{5NP-P}{2(1+2N+P+NP)}  ≈2.5=Θ​(1)\\approx 2.5=\\Theta(1) |\n\n(a) SISO (2-byte data).\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Input | Output | FLOPs | Arithmetic Intensity |\n| Ht:(N,P)H\\_{t}:(N,P)  xt:(P,R)x\\_{t}:(P,R)  at:(1)a\\_{t}:(1)  bt:(N,R)b\\_{t}:(N,R)  ct:(N,R)c\\_{t}:(N,R) | yt:(P,R)y\\_{t}:(P,R) | 4​N​P​R+N​P−P​R4NPR+NP-PR | 4​N​P​R+N​P−P​R2​(1+2​N​R+P​R+N​P)\\displaystyle\\frac{4NPR+NP-PR}{2(1+2NR+PR+NP)}  =Θ​(min⁡(N,P,R))=\\Theta(\\min(N,P,R))  =Θ​(R)=\\Theta(R), R≪N,PR\\ll N,P |\n\n(b) MIMO (2-byte data).\n\n##### From SISO to MIMO.\n\nConsider a single head of a typical SSM with *head dimension* PP, which involves stacking the SISO recurrence 𝒉t←αt​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​xt{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\leftarrow\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t} with PP copies sharing the same αt,Δt\\alpha\\_{t},\\Delta\\_{t} and 𝑩t{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}. The resulting broadcasted recurrence 𝒉t←αt​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​𝒙t⊤{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\leftarrow\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}^{\\top} takes vector inputs 𝒙t∈ℝP{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{P} and has matrix-valued states 𝒉t∈ℝN×P{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times P}.\n\nNote that the memory traffic (input and output size) is dominated by the state 𝒉t{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}, while the computation mainly comprises the outer product 𝑩t​𝒙t⊤{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}^{\\top} which has FLOPs proportional to N​PNP. By increasing the dimension of the latter terms, transforming 𝑩t∈ℝN→𝑩t∈ℝN×R{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N}\\to{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times R} and 𝒙t∈ℝP→𝒙t∈ℝP×R{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{P}\\to{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{P\\times R}, the memory traffic does not significantly increase (for small RR) while the FLOPs consumed increase by a factor of RR ([Table˜2(a)](#S3.T2.st1 \"In Table 2 ‣ Decoding Arithmetic Intensity. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). Thus, this transformation increases the arithmetic intensity of the recurrence. Furthermore, the increase in arithmetic intensity is translated into practical gains, since the outer product 𝑩t​𝒙t⊤{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}^{\\top} becomes a hardware-efficient matrix-matrix product (matmul), which is computed using fast tensor-cores, incurring only a marginal latency cost. As a result, the MIMO recurrence is more expressive than the original SISO recurrence, computing R×R{\\scriptstyle\\times} more FLOPs while practically preserving the decoding speed.\n\nFor similar reasons, the computation of the output from the state, 𝒚t←𝑪t⊤​𝒉t{\\bm{y}}\\_{t}\\leftarrow{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} acquires an extra rank RR by modifying the output projection as 𝑪t∈ℝN→𝑪t∈ℝN×R{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N}\\to{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N\\times R}. Overall, this transformation is equivalent to expanding the original single-input, single-output (SISO) recurrence to multi-input, multi-output (MIMO).\n\n##### Training MIMO SSMs.\n\nWhile the MIMO formulation is motivated by *inference* efficiency, the *training* algorithms for SSMs (including our developments in [Section˜3.1](#S3.SS1 \"3.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), [Section˜3.2](#S3.SS2 \"3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) have been typically developed for SISO models. We begin with the observation that MIMO SSMs can be expressed in terms of R2R^{2} SISO SSMs, where RR SISO SSMs sharing the same recurrence are summed for each of the RR MIMO outputs. In particular, define 𝑪t(i)∈ℝN,𝑩t(j)∈ℝN,𝒙t(j)∈ℝ,Δt∈ℝ{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{(i)}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N},{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}^{(j)}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N},{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}^{(j)}\\in\\mathbb{R},\\Delta\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}, where i,j∈{0,…,R−1}i,j\\in\\{0,...,R-1\\}, then we have,\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t(j)\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}^{(j)} | ←αt​𝒉t−1(j)+Δt​𝑩t(j)​𝒙t(j)\\displaystyle\\leftarrow\\alpha\\_{t}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}^{(j)}+\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}^{(j)}{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}^{(j)} | (12) |\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t\\displaystyle{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | =∑j=0R−1𝒉t(j)\\displaystyle=\\sum\\_{j=0}^{R-1}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}^{(j)} | (13) |\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 𝒚t(i)\\displaystyle{\\bm{y}}\\_{t}^{(i)} | ←(𝑪t(i))⊤​𝒉t\\displaystyle\\leftarrow\\left({\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{(i)}\\right)^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t} | (14) |\n\nThus, yt(i)=∑j𝖲𝖲𝖬​(α,Δ,𝑩(j),𝑪(i),𝒙(j))ty\\_{t}^{(i)}=\\sum\\_{j}\\mathsf{SSM}\\!\\left(\\alpha,\\Delta,{\\bm{B}}^{(j)},{\\bm{C}}^{(i)},{\\bm{x}}^{(j)}\\right)\\_{t}, where 𝖲𝖲𝖬​(α,Δ,𝑩(j),𝑪(i),𝒙(j))t:=(𝑪t(i))⊤​𝒉t(j)\\mathsf{SSM}\\!\\left(\\alpha,\\Delta,{\\bm{B}}^{(j)},{\\bm{C}}^{(i)},{\\bm{x}}^{(j)}\\right)\\_{t}:=\\left({\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{(i)}\\right)^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}^{(j)} with 𝒉t(j){\\bm{h}}\\_{t}^{(j)} from ([12](#S3.E12 \"Equation 12 ‣ Training MIMO SSMs. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).\n\nFurthermore, improvements to standard SISO-based SSM models can be directly applied to MIMO models as the underlying SISO training algorithms can be utilized as a black-box. This observation allows a MIMO model to be trained by invoking the SISO algorithm R2R^{2} times as a black box in parallel. In contrast, when computed in the recurrent form, equation ([12](#S3.E12 \"Equation 12 ‣ Training MIMO SSMs. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), ([13](#S3.E13 \"Equation 13 ‣ Training MIMO SSMs. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), and ([14](#S3.E14 \"Equation 14 ‣ Training MIMO SSMs. ‣ 3.3 Multi-Input, Multi-Output ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) can be performed sequentially, incurring only an RR-times overhead relative to SISO SSMs (recall the discussion on MIMO decoding FLOPs).\n\n##### Chunked Algorithm for MIMO SSMs.\n\nMany modern SISO recurrent models, including Mamba-2, are computed using a *chunked* algorithm, where the sequence is divided into chunks of length CC. Within each chunk, a parallel (but asymptotically slower) algorithm is applied, while a recurrence is computed across chunks. Chunked algorithms interpolate between two extremes: a fully parallel and a fully sequential algorithm. By exploiting this structure, we can reduce the training cost of MIMO SSMs to RR times that of SISO SSMs. This idea also appears in the SSD framework—SSD applies a hardware-friendly quadratic algorithm within each chunk, while using the recurrent form across chunks, and shows that when the state and head dimensions are comparable, setting the chunk size to this dimension yields an overall linear-time algorithm. Specifically, SSD’s intra-chunk computation incurs (2​C2​N+2​C2​P)\\left(2C^{2}N+2C^{2}P\\right) FLOPs per chunk, giving a total of TC​(2​C2​N+2​C2​P)=2​T​C​(N+P)\\frac{T}{C}\\left(2C^{2}N+2C^{2}P\\right)=2TC(N+P). The inter-chunk computation incurs 4​N​P​C+2​N​P4NPC+2NP FLOPs per chunk, for a total of TC​(4​N​P​C+2​N​P)=4​T​N​P+TC​2​N​P\\frac{T}{C}(4NPC+2NP)=4TNP+\\frac{T}{C}2NP (ignoring negligible terms). Setting C=P=NC=P=N, the total FLOP count is 8​T​N28TN^{2}, which is linear in TT.\n\nThe chunked algorithm for SSD can be naturally generalized into MIMO SSMs. In such a case, the FLOP counts of state projection 𝑩​𝒙⊤{\\bm{B}}{\\bm{x}}^{\\top} and state emission 𝑪⊤​𝒉{\\bm{C}}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}} increase by R×R\\times, while the FLOP count of the intrachunk component 𝑪⊤​𝑩{\\bm{C}}^{\\top}{\\bm{B}} increases by R2×R^{2}\\times. As a result, the intra-chunk computation incurs 2⋅(TC​(C​R)2​N+TC​(C​R)2​P)2\\cdot\\left(\\frac{T}{C}(CR)^{2}N+\\frac{T}{C}(CR)^{2}P\\right) FLOPs and inter-chunk computation incurs 4⋅TC​N​P​(C​R)+2⋅TC​N​P4\\cdot\\frac{T}{C}NP(CR)+2\\cdot\\frac{T}{C}NP FLOPs. Thus, setting C​R=N=PCR=N=P yields a total FLOP count of 8​T​R​N28TRN^{2}, an RR-fold increase in FLOP count. Intuitively, setting MIMO chunk size as 1R\\frac{1}{R} times the SISO chunk size, i.e., CMIMO←1R​CSISOC\\_{\\text{MIMO}}\\leftarrow\\frac{1}{R}C\\_{\\text{SISO}}, maintains the SISO intra-chunk FLOP count while increasing the number of chunks by a factor of RR, resulting in an overall RR-times increase in FLOP count instead of an R2R^{2}-times increase while keeping the algorithm hardware-friendly.\n\nThe training speed of algorithms in practice depends on details of the kernel implementation strategy, architectural choices such as how the MIMO parameters are instantiated, and problem dimensions, but should be no more than RR times slower. Our released Triton Mamba-3 SISO kernels are roughly on par with the Triton Mamba-2 kernels, and MIMO kernels only incur a slowdown of 2×2{\\scriptstyle\\times} when R=4R=4, as compute latency can be parallelized with memory movement. [Table˜6](#S4.T6 \"In 4.3 Inference Efficiency to Performance Tradeoff ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") benchmarks the prefill speed of various kernels which is equivalent to the forward pass of the training kernel.\n\n##### MIMO Instantiation.\n\nAmong various choices for MIMO parameterizations, Mamba-3’s approach achieves a balance that preserves the state size and number of SSMs of its SISO counterpart, while avoiding excessive growth in parameter count. The naive conversion of a SISO SSM to a rank RR MIMO SSM would incur an R×R\\times increase in parameters as all projections that model the inputs to the SSM, 𝑩,𝑪,𝒙{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}},{\\bm{x}}, would increase. Block-level components, such as the gate 𝒛{\\bm{z}} (which so far has been ignored for simplicity) and output 𝒚{\\bm{y}} projection would also be impacted. This influx in parameter count would be intractable at larger model scales. To counteract this, we make the following change. Mamba’s multi-value attention (MVA) head structure results in shared 𝑩,𝑪{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}} across heads, so these components’ projections can be directly converted to incorporate the new MIMO rank RR with only a slight increase in parameter count from D​NDN to D​N​RDNR for the entire layer (recall DD as the model dimension). However, the SSM input 𝒙t{\\bm{x}}\\_{t}, output 𝒚t{\\bm{y}}\\_{t}, and gate 𝒛t{\\bm{z}}\\_{t} are unique per head and therefore dominate the parameter count. Here, directly adjusting the projections would increase the parameter count from D​PDP to D​P​RDPR for *each head*. Instead, we keep the original SISO projection and element-wise scale each dimension of the projected output to size RR with a learnable, data-independent vector, resulting in D​P+P​RDP+PR parameters for each head. This mitigates the multiplicative increase to a more reasonable additive parameter count increase. [Appendix˜C](#A3 \"Appendix C MIMO for Mamba-3 ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") details the parameterization, and all MIMO-variants in our paper are parameter-matched to their SISO counterparts by reducing the MLP width.\n\n###### Remark 6.\n\nFor simplicity, all discussion in this section was for simpler 2-term recurrences such as that arising from exponential-Euler discretization; the generalization to the 3-term exponential-trapezoidal recurrence is similar.\n\n### 3.4 Mamba-3 Architecture\n\n![Refer to caption](2603.15569v1/x2.png) \n\nFigure 2: Contrasting Mamba-2 and Mamba-3 Architectures: Key updates include exponential-trapezoidal discretization, data-dependent RoPE embeddings, MIMO projections, QK normalization, and learnable biases.\n\n \n\nThe overall architecture follows Llama [grattafiori2024llama3herdmodels], alternating Mamba-3 and SwiGLU blocks with pre-norm. The Mamba-3 block retains the overall layout of its predecessor, while introducing several key modifications.\n\n##### Updated SSM Recurrence.\n\nThe SSD layer is replaced with the more expressive complex-valued exponential-trapezoidal SSM defined in Proposition [3.2.2](#S3.SS2.SSS2 \"3.2.2 Complex SSM with Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"). Mamba-3 employs the SISO SSM by default to enable fair comparisons with other SISO-like models, but its MIMO variant can be trained and deployed as a stronger alternative to baseline Mamba-3 ([Table˜3](#S4.T3 \"In 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). Our SSM 𝑨{\\bm{A}} is complex with both real and imaginary components produced by data-dependent projections. With [Figure˜2](#S3.F2 \"In 3.4 Mamba-3 Architecture ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), this is partitioned into the real-valued AA and imaginary-valued Θ\\Theta; the former is passed into the SSD black box as in Mamba-2, while the latter is computed through the RoPE trick.\n\n##### BC / QK Normalization.\n\nRMS normalizations are added following the 𝑩,𝑪{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}} projection, mirroring the QKNorm commonly used in modern Transformers [henry2020querykeynormalizationtransformers, wortsman2023smallscaleproxieslargescaletransformer] and other recent linear models [yang2025gateddeltanetworksimproving, hu2025combaimprovingbilinearrnns]. We call this either BC normalization (BCNorm) or QK normalization (QKNorm) interchangeably. We find that BCNorm is also able to stabilize large-scale runs, resulting in the removal of the post-gate RMSNorm layer (introduced in Mamba-2 for stability) in our pure Mamba-3 models. However, in hybrid models, the removed RMSNorm layer is crucial for long-context extrapolation ([Table˜4](#S4.T4 \"In Improving Retrieval with Hybrid Models. ‣ 4.1.2 Retrieval Capabilities ‣ 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).\n\n##### 𝑩,𝑪{\\bm{B}},{\\bm{C}} Biases.\n\nSimilarly to [yu2025blockbiasedmamba], which proved that adding channel-specific biases to 𝑩{\\bm{B}} in a blockwise variant of Mamba-1 grants universal approximation capabilities, Mamba-3 incorporates learnable, head-specific, channel-wise biases into the 𝑩{\\bm{B}} and 𝑪{\\bm{C}} components after the BCNorm.\n\nWe hypothesize that these biases also induce a convolution-like behavior in the model. Specifically, adding biases to 𝑩{\\bm{B}} and 𝑪{\\bm{C}} introduces data-independent components into SSMs that function more similarly to convolutions. Ablations on the bias parameterization are located in [Appendix˜F](#A6 \"Appendix F Architecture Ablations ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nThe combination of data-independent bias parameters, together with exponential-trapezoidal discretization (which itself induces a convolution on the state-input), is empirically able to obviate the short causal convolution and its accompanying activation function present in Mamba-2 and most modern recurrent models ([Section˜4.2](#S4.SS2 \"4.2 SSM Methodology Ablations ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")).\n\n## 4 Empirical Validation\n\nWe empirically validate our SSM-centric methodological changes through the Mamba-3 model on a host of synthetic and real-world tasks. [Section˜4.1](#S4.SS1 \"4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") evaluates Mamba-3 on language modeling and retrieval-based tasks. [Section˜4.2](#S4.SS2 \"4.2 SSM Methodology Ablations ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") ablates the effect of our new SSM components such as discretization and complex transitions. [Section˜4.3](#S4.SS3 \"4.3 Inference Efficiency to Performance Tradeoff ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") explores the inference efficiency of the Mamba-3 family and MIMO Mamba-3’s benefits over the SISO variant under fixed inference compute, and [Section˜4.4](#S4.SS4 \"4.4 Fast Mamba-3 Kernels ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") benchmarks the performance of our Mamba-3 training and inference kernels.\n\n### 4.1 Language Modeling\n\n \n\nTable 3: Downstream language modeling evaluations on models trained with 100B FineWeb-Edu tokens. Best results for each size are bolded, and second best are underlined, excluding Mamba-3 MIMO variants. All models are trained with the same procedure. Mamba-3 SISO outperforms Mamba-2 and others at every model scale, and the MIMO variant with rank R=4R=4 further improves modeling capabilities.