8.7 | 58.858.8 | 28.628.6 | 53.753.753.7 |\n| Mamba-2-880M | 11.3511.3511.35 | 13.813.8 | 45.045.0 | 58.158.158.1 | 72.572.5 | 72.372.372.3 | 38.738.7 | 56.856.8 | 30.230.2 | 53.453.4 |\n| Mamba-3-SISO-880M | 11.2311.23 | 12.912.9 | 47.247.247.2 | 58.858.8 | 73.673.6 | 72.772.7 | 40.240.2 | 58.458.458.4 | 30.030.030.0 | 54.454.4 |\n| Mamba-3-MIMO-880M | 11.1111.11 | 11.811.8 | 49.549.5 | 59.259.2 | 73.773.7 | 74.774.7 | 41.241.2 | 59.959.9 | 28.628.6 | 55.355.3 |\n| Transformer-1.5B | 10.5110.51 | 11.111.1 | 50.350.3 | 60.660.6 | 73.873.873.8 | 74.074.0 | 40.440.4 | 58.758.758.7 | 29.629.6 | 55.455.4 |\n| GDN-1.5B | 10.4510.4510.45 | 10.910.9 | 49.249.2 | 61.361.3 | 74.374.3 | 75.375.375.3 | 41.241.2 | 58.058.0 | 31.631.6 | 55.855.855.8 |\n| Mamba-2-1.5B | 10.4710.47 | 12.012.0 | 47.847.8 | 61.461.461.4 | 73.673.6 | 75.375.375.3 | 41.841.841.8 | 57.557.5 | 32.632.6 | 55.755.7 |\n| Mamba-3-SISO-1.5B | 10.3510.35 | 10.910.9 | 49.449.449.4 | 61.961.9 | 73.673.6 | 75.975.9 | 42.742.7 | 59.459.4 | 32.032.032.0 | 56.456.4 |\n| Mamba-3-MIMO-1.5B | 10.2410.24 | 10.210.2 | 51.751.7 | 62.362.3 | 75.375.3 | 76.576.5 | 44.544.5 | 60.660.6 | 32.632.6 | 57.657.6 |\n\nAll models are pretrained with 100B tokens of the FineWeb-Edu dataset [penedo2024finewebdatasetsdecantingweb] with the Llama-3.1 tokenizer [grattafiori2024llama3herdmodels] at a 2K context length with the same standard training protocol. Training and evaluation details can be found in [Appendix˜D](#A4 \"Appendix D Experimental Details ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nAcross all four model scales, Mamba-3 outperforms popular baselines at various downstream tasks ([Table˜3](#S4.T3 \"In 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")). We highlight that Mamba-3 does not utilize the external short convolution that has been empirically identified as an important component in many performant linear models [gu2024mambalineartimesequencemodeling, yang2025gateddeltanetworksimproving, allen2025canon].\n\n#### 4.1.1 MIMO\n\nWe aim to further verify the gain from MIMO by investigating its language-modeling capabilities by training MIMO models with rank R=4R=4 under the same settings. To ensure that the total parameter count is comparable to SISO-based models, we decrease the inner dimension of the MLP layers in MIMO models to compensate for the increase due to the MIMO projections. In the 1.5B-parameter models, for instance, the MLP inner dimension is reduced by only 6.6%6.6\\%, from 4096 to 3824. See [Appendix˜C](#A3 \"Appendix C MIMO for Mamba-3 ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") for more details.\n\nOn both validation perplexity and our suite of language evaluation tasks ([Table˜3](#S4.T3 \"In 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), we see significant gains when moving from SISO to MIMO for our Mamba-3 models. Namely, we achieve a significant perplexity gain of 0.110.11 on the 1.5B models, and [Figure˜3](#S4.F3 \"In 4.3 Inference Efficiency to Performance Tradeoff ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") illustrates the downward shift in our validation loss. On the language evaluation front, we see gains on most tasks when compared to SISO, resulting in an average gain of 1.2 percentage points over SISO.\n\n#### 4.1.2 Retrieval Capabilities\n\nBeyond standard language modeling, an important measure for linear models is their retrieval ability—how well they can recall information from earlier in the sequence [arora2025mechanisticevaluationtransformersstate, arora2025simplelinearattentionlanguage]. Unlike attention models, which can freely revisit past context with the growing KV cache, linear models must compress context into a fixed-size state. This trade-off is reflected in the Transformer baseline’s substantially stronger retrieval scores. To evaluate Mamba-3 under this lens, [Table˜4](#S4.T4 \"In Improving Retrieval with Hybrid Models. ‣ 4.1.2 Retrieval Capabilities ‣ 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\") compares it against baselines on both real-world and synthetic needle-in-a-haystack (NIAH) tasks [hsieh2024rulerwhatsrealcontext], using our pretrained 1.5B models from [Section˜4.1](#S4.SS1 \"4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"). We restrict the task sequence length to 2K tokens to match the training setup and adopt the cloze-style format for our real-world tasks to mirror the next-token-prediction objective, following [arora2025simplelinearattentionlanguage, arora2024justreadtwiceclosing].\n\nMamba-3 is competitive on real-world associative recall and question-answering (TQA, SQuAD) but struggles when extracting information from semi-structured or unstructured data (SWDE, FDA). On synthetic NIAH tasks, however, Mamba-3 surpasses or matches baselines on most cases and notably demonstrates markedly better out-of-distribution retrieval abilities than its Mamba-2 predecessor.\n\n##### Improving Retrieval with Hybrid Models.\n\nBecause of the natural retrieval-based weaknesses of fixed state-size, we predict that linear layers will be predominantly used *in hybrid architectures* that mitigate this downside with quadratic self-attention layers. To evaluate how Mamba-3 performs within this architectural paradigm, we train our hybrid models at the same scale in an interleaving fashion with a 5:1 ratio of linear layer to NoPE self-attention [yang2025ropenopeagainnew]. As seen in prior work [waleffe2024empiricalstudymambabasedlanguage], hybrid models outperform the Transformer baseline. We find that the reintroduction of the pre-output projection RMSNorm (pre-gate, grouped RMSNorm in [Table˜4](#S4.T4 \"In Improving Retrieval with Hybrid Models. ‣ 4.1.2 Retrieval Capabilities ‣ 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) to the Mamba-3 layer improves the length generalization retrieval abilities at the slight cost of in-context, real-world retrieval tasks and is highly competitive as a linear sequence mixing backbone when mixed with self-attention. However, the ideal norm type (grouped vs default) and its placement (pre- vs post-gate) is still unclear due to competing tradeoffs ([Appendix˜E](#A5 \"Appendix E Additional Experimental Results ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), [Table˜9](#A5.T9 \"In Appendix E Additional Experimental Results ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), as we find that hybrid models and their exact characteristics and dynamics are complex and oftentimes unintuitive, a point echoed in recent works such as [cabannes2025shortwindowattentionenables].\n\n \n\nTable 4: Retrieval capabilities measured by a mixture of real-world and synthetic retrieval tasks. Real-world retrieval tasks utilize cloze variants of the original datasets and are truncated to 2K length. Mamba-3 demonstrates strong associative recall, question-answering, and length generalization on needle-in-a-haystack (NIAH), but suffers with information extraction of semi-structured and unstructured data. The Transformer baseline uses RoPE which may explain its length generalization issues, and hybrid models utilize NoPE (no positional embeddings). We find a pre-gate, grouped RMSNorm can be added to Mamba-3 SISO hybrid models to improve the length generalization of the NIAH tasks at a slight decrease in real-world retrieval performance.\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Model (1.5B) | SWDE | SQD. | FDA | TQA | NQ | Drop | NIAH-Single-1 | NIAH-Single-2 | NIAH-Single-3 |\n| Context Length | 2048 | 1024 