approximated the exponential dynamics of the adjusted underlying ODE and leave the state-input integral to be approximated with any host of methods. ∎\n\n### A.1 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization’s Mask Matrix\n\n###### Proof.\n\nWhen viewing the tensor contraction form, let us call C=(T,N),B=(S,N),L=(T,S),X=(S,P)C=(T,N),B=(S,N),L=(T,S),X=(S,P) based on the Mamba-2 paper. With this decomposition of our mask, we can view L=contract​(T​Z,Z​S→T​S)​(L1,L2)L=\\text{contract}(TZ,ZS\\rightarrow TS)(L\\_{1},L\\_{2}).\n\nThe original contraction can be seen as\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| contract​(T​N,S​N,T​S,S​P→T​P)​(C,B,L,X)\\text{contract}(TN,SN,TS,SP\\rightarrow TP)(C,B,L,X) |\n\nWe can now view it as\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| contract​(T​N,S​N,T​J,J​S,S​P→T​P)​(C,B,L1,L2,X)\\text{contract}(TN,SN,TJ,JS,SP\\rightarrow TP)(C,B,L\\_{1},L\\_{2},X) |\n\nThis can be broken into the following:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Z\\displaystyle Z | =contract​(S​N,S​P→S​N​P)​(B,X)\\displaystyle=\\text{contract}(SN,SP\\rightarrow SNP)(B,X) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Z′\\displaystyle Z^{\\prime} | =contract​(J​S,S​N​P→J​N​P)​(L2,Z)\\displaystyle=\\text{contract}(JS,SNP\\rightarrow JNP)(L\\_{2},Z) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| H\\displaystyle H | =contract​(T​J,J​N​P→T​N​P)​(L1,Z′)\\displaystyle=\\text{contract}(TJ,JNP\\rightarrow TNP)(L\\_{1},Z^{\\prime}) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Y\\displaystyle Y | =contract​(T​N,T​N​P→T​P)​(C,H)\\displaystyle=\\text{contract}(TN,TNP\\rightarrow TP)(C,H) |\n\nWe can view this step: contract​(Z​S,S​N​P→Z​N​P)​(L2,Z)\\text{contract}(ZS,SNP\\rightarrow ZNP)(L\\_{2},Z) as a convolution of size two applied on the state-input (B,XB,X outer product) prior to the decay with the traditional SSD L=L1L=L\\_{1} matrix. ∎\n\n### A.2 Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization Error Rate\n\n##### Standard assumptions.\n\nWe assume that: A​(t),𝑩​(t),x​(t)A(t),{\\bm{B}}(t),x(t) are bounded and C3C^{3} on each timestep, so that g​(τ)g(\\tau) has three bounded derivatives; the map 𝒉↦A​(t)​𝒉+𝑩​(t)​x​(t){\\bm{h}}\\mapsto A(t){\\bm{h}}+{\\bm{B}}(t)x(t) is Lipschitz in 𝒉{\\bm{h}} which is true for linear systems; λt\\lambda\\_{t} lies in a bounded interval so that the update is zero-stable.\n\n###### Proof.\n\nLet 𝒈​(τ)≔e(tk−τ)​Ak​𝑩​(τ)​x​(τ){\\bm{g}}(\\tau)\\coloneqq e^{(t\\_{k}-\\tau)A\\_{k}}\\,{\\bm{B}}(\\tau)x(\\tau) denote the integrand in the second term of Proposition [A](#A1 \"Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"). Since A​(t),𝑩​(t),x​(t)A(t),{\\bm{B}}(t),x(t) are C3C^{3} on [tk−1,tk][t\\_{k-1},t\\_{k}], the function gg has three bounded derivatives. A second-order Taylor expansion of gg around tk−1t\\_{k-1} gives us,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| ∫tk−1tkg​(τ)​𝑑τ=Δt​g​(tk−1)+Δt22​g′​(tk−1)+Δt36​g′′​(tk−1)+O​(Δt4).\\displaystyle\\int\\_{t\\_{k-1}}^{t\\_{k}}g(\\tau)\\,d\\tau=\\Delta\\_{t}\\,g(t\\_{k-1})+\\frac{\\Delta\\_{t}^{2}}{2}\\,g^{\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+\\frac{\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}}{6}\\,g^{\\prime\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{4}). |\n\nRecall that the trapezoidal approximation to this integral is given by,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| Qλ=Δt​[(1−λt)​g​(tk−1)+λt​g​(tk)].\\displaystyle Q\\_{\\lambda}=\\Delta\\_{t}\\Big[(1-\\lambda\\_{t})\\,g(t\\_{k-1})+\\lambda\\_{t}\\,g(t\\_{k})\\Big]. |\n\nExpanding g​(tk)g(t\\_{k}) using Taylor expansion: g​(tk)=g​(tk−1)+Δt​g′​(tk−1)+Δt22​g′′​(tk−1)+O​(Δt3)g(t\\_{k})=g(t\\_{k-1})+\\Delta\\_{t}g^{\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+\\frac{\\Delta\\_{t}^{2}}{2}g^{\\prime\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}). Substituting this into QλQ\\_{\\lambda},\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Qλ\\displaystyle Q\\_{\\lambda} | =Δt​[(1−λt)​g​(tk−1)+λt​g​(tk)]\\displaystyle=\\Delta\\_{t}\\Big[(1-\\lambda\\_{t})g(t\\_{k-1})+\\lambda\\_{t}g(t\\_{k})\\Big] |\n|  |\n| --- |\n| =Δt​g​(tk−1)+λt​Δt2​g′​(tk−1)+λt​Δt32​g′′​(tk−1)+O​(Δt4).\\displaystyle=\\Delta\\_{t}g(t\\_{k-1})+\\lambda\\_{t}\\Delta\\_{t}^{2}g^{\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+\\lambda\\_{t}\\frac{\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}}{2}g^{\\prime\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{4}). |\n\nHence, the error is given by:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| ∫tk−1tkg​(τ)​𝑑τ−Qλ\\displaystyle\\int\\_{t\\_{k-1}}^{t\\_{k}}g(\\tau)\\,d\\tau-Q\\_{\\lambda} | =(12−λt)​Δt2​g′​(tk−1)+(16−λt2)​Δt3​g′′​(tk−1)+O​(Δt4).\\displaystyle=\\Big(\\tfrac{1}{2}-\\lambda\\_{t}\\Big)\\Delta\\_{t}^{2}g^{\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+\\Big(\\tfrac{1}{6}-\\tfrac{\\lambda\\_{t}}{2}\\Big)\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}g^{\\prime\\prime}(t\\_{k-1})+O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{4}). |\n\nUnder the assumption that λt=12+ct​Δt\\lambda\\_{t}=\\tfrac{1}{2}+c\\_{t}\\Delta\\_{t}, where ct=O​(1)c\\_{t}=O(1), then 12−λt=−ct​Δt=O​(Δt)\\tfrac{1}{2}-\\lambda\\_{t}=-c\\_{t}\\Delta\\_{t}=O(\\Delta\\_{t}) and thus the Δt2\\Delta\\_{t}^{2} term is O​(Δt3)O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}). Therefore,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| ∫tk−1tkg​(τ)​𝑑τ−Qλ=O​(Δt3),\\displaystyle\\int\\_{t\\_{k-1}}^{t\\_{k}}g(\\tau)\\,d\\tau-Q\\_{\\lambda}=O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}), |\n\nwhich yields an O​(Δt3)O(\\Delta\\_{t}^{3}) local truncation error. ∎\n\n### A.3 Exponential-Trapezoidal Parameterization\n\n \n\nTable 8: Ablations on λt\\lambda\\_{t} parameterization in the exponential-trapezoidal update.\n\n| Parameterization | Form of λt\\lambda\\_{t} | ppl ↓\\downarrow |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Default | σ​(ut)\\sigma(u\\_{t}) | 15.72 |\n| Fixed 1/21/2 | 12\\tfrac{1}{2} | 15.76 |\n| No trapezoidal (Euler) | 11 | 15.81 |\n\nSetting: All runs use the Mamba-3 (SISO) 440M model trained at Chinchilla scale, with the other architectural and optimization hyperparameters being the same as in Table [3](#S4.T3 \"Table 3 ‣ 4.1 Language Modeling ‣ 4 Empirical Validation ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\").\n\nThe default model uses a data-dependent gate λt=σ​(ut)\\lambda\\_{t}=\\sigma(u\\_{t}), where utu\\_{t} is a learned projection of the current input token. In [Table˜8](#A1.T8 \"In A.3 Exponential-Trapezoidal Parameterization ‣ Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\"), we try different parameterizations for λt\\lambda\\_{t} and find that the default parameterization empirically performs the best. Hence, we choose the simpler default parameterization that does *not* enforce λt=12+O​(Δt)\\lambda\\_{t}=\\tfrac{1}{2}+O(\\Delta\\_{t}).\n\n## Appendix B Complex SSM Proofs\n\n### B.1 Proof of Proposition [3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n\n\\PropComplexRealSSM\n\n\\*\n\n###### Proof..\n\nWe first present the derivation for N=2N=2; the block-diagonal structure for general even NN follows by grouping pairs of coordinates.\n\nLet ht+i​h^th\\_{t}+i\\hat{h}\\_{t} denote the complexified hidden state, with parameters A​(t)+i​θ​(t)A(t)+i\\theta(t) and B​(t)+i​B^​(t)B(t)+i\\hat{B}(t) for the transition and input, respectively. By the variation of constants formula (Proposition [A](#A1 \"Appendix A Exponential-Trapezoidal Discretization ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")), applying zero-order hold and Euler’s rule over a step [tk−1,tk][t\\_{k-1},t\\_{k}] gives\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| hk+i​h^k=eΔt​(At+i​θt)​(hk−1+i​h^k−1)+Δt​(Bt+i​B^t)​xt.h\\_{k}+i\\hat{h}\\_{k}=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}(A\\_{t}+i\\theta\\_{t})}(h\\_{k-1}+i\\hat{h}\\_{k-1})+\\Delta\\_{t}(B\\_{t}+i\\hat{B}\\_{t})x\\_{t}. |\n\nExpanding the exponential,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| eΔt​(At+i​θt)=eΔt​At​(cos⁡(Δt​θt)+i​sin⁡(Δt​θt)),e^{\\Delta\\_{t}(A\\_{t}+i\\theta\\_{t})}=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\Big(\\cos(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})+i\\sin(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})\\Big), |\n\nso in real coordinates 𝒉t=[hth^t]∈ℝ2{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=\\begin{bmatrix}h\\_{t}\\\\ \\hat{h}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2} the recurrence becomes\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| 𝒉t=eΔt​At​[cos⁡(Δt​θt)−sin⁡(Δt​θt)sin⁡(Δt​θt)cos⁡(Δt​θt)]⏟R​(Δt​θt)​𝒉t−1+Δt​[BtB^t]​xt.{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\underbrace{\\begin{bmatrix}\\cos(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})&-\\sin(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})\\\\ \\sin(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})&\\cos(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})\\end{bmatrix}}\\_{R(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t})}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}\\begin{bmatrix}B\\_{t}\\\\ \\hat{B}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}x\\_{t}. |\n\nStacking across N/2N/2 such pairs yields the block-diagonal transition\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| 𝒉t=eΔt​At​Block​({R​(Δt​θt​[i])}i=1N/2)​𝒉t−1+Δt​[𝑩t𝑩^t]​xt.{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}=e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\,\\mathrm{Block}\\big(\\{R(\\Delta\\_{t}\\theta\\_{t}[i])\\}\\_{i=1}^{N/2}\\big){\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}+\\Delta\\_{t}\\begin{bmatrix}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}\\\\ \\hat{{\\bm{B}}}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}x\\_{t}. |\n\nFor the output,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| yt=Re​((𝑪t+i​𝑪^t)⊤​(ht+i​h^t))=[𝑪t−𝑪^t]⊤​𝒉t,y\\_{t}=\\mathrm{Re}\\Big(({\\bm{C}}\\_{t}+i\\hat{{\\bm{C}}}\\_{t})^{\\top}(h\\_{t}+i\\hat{h}\\_{t})\\Big)=\\begin{bmatrix}{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\\\ -\\hat{{\\bm{C}}}\\_{t}\\end{bmatrix}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}, |\n\nwhich defines the real projection 𝑪t∈ℝN{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{N} in the proposition. This proves the equivalence between complex SSM and the real block-diagonal system with rotations. ∎\n\n### B.2 Proof of Proposition [3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")\n\n\\PropRoPETrick\n\n\\*\n\n###### Proof..\n\nConsider the SSM\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t=eΔt​At​𝑹t​𝒉t−1+Δt​𝑩t​xt,yt=𝑪t⊤​𝒉t,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\;=\\;e^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}}\\,{\\bm{R}}\\_{t}\\,{\\bm{h}}\\_{t-1}\\;+\\;\\Delta\\_{t}{\\bm{B}}\\_{t}x\\_{t},\\qquad y\\_{t}\\;=\\;{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}, | (17) |\n\nwhere (as in Proposition [3.2.1](#S3.SS2.SSS1 \"3.2.1 Complex SSM with Exponential-Euler Discretization ‣ 3.2 Complex-Valued SSMs ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ Mamba-3: Improved Sequence Modeling using State Space Principles\")) At∈ℝA\\_{t}\\in\\mathbb{R} is a scalar (so that eΔt​Ate^{\\Delta\\_{t}A\\_{t}} is a scalar and commutes with rotations), and 𝑹t{\\bm{R}}\\_{t} is block-diagonal orthogonal/unitary, hence 𝑹t−1=𝑹t⊤{\\bm{R}}\\_{t}^{-1}={\\bm{R}}\\_{t}^{\\top} and the matrices 𝑹i,𝑹j{\\bm{R}}\\_{i},{\\bm{R}}\\_{j} commute, i.e. 𝑹i​𝑹j=𝑹j​𝑹i{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}{\\bm{R}}\\_{j}={\\bm{R}}\\_{j}{\\bm{R}}\\_{i}.\n\nUnrolling the recurrence with the convention that an empty product is the identity,\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒉t=∑i=0t(∏s=i+1teΔs​As​𝑹s)​Δi​𝑩i​xi.{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\;=\\;\\sum\\_{i=0}^{t}\\bigg(\\prod\\_{s=i+1}^{t}e^{\\Delta\\_{s}A\\_{s}}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\bigg)\\,\\Delta\\_{i}{\\bm{B}}\\_{i}x\\_{i}. | (18) |\n\nThus\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| yt=𝑪t⊤​𝒉t=∑i=0t𝑪t⊤​(∏s=i+1teΔs​As​𝑹s)​Δi​𝑩i​xi.\\displaystyle y\\_{t}\\;=\\;{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}{\\bm{h}}\\_{t}\\;=\\;\\sum\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}\\bigg(\\prod\\_{s=i+1}^{t}e^{\\Delta\\_{s}A\\_{s}}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\bigg)\\Delta\\_{i}{\\bm{B}}\\_{i}x\\_{i}. | (19) |\n\nUsing its unitary property,\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| ∏s=i+1t𝑹s=(∏s=0t𝑹s)​(∏s=0i𝑹s)−1=(∏s=0t𝑹s)​(∏s=0i𝑹s⊤).\\displaystyle\\prod\\_{s=i+1}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}=\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\right)\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{i}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\right)^{-1}=\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\right)\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{i}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}^{\\top}\\right). |\n\nSince eΔs​Ase^{\\Delta\\_{s}A\\_{s}} are scalars, they commute with rotations; hence\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| yt\\displaystyle y\\_{t} | =∑i=0t𝑪t⊤​(∏s=0t𝑹s)​(∏s=i+1teΔs​As)​(∏s=0i𝑹s⊤)​Δi​𝑩i​xi\\displaystyle=\\sum\\_{i=0}^{t}{\\bm{C}}\\_{t}^{\\top}\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}\\right)\\left(\\prod\\_{s=i+1}^{t}e^{\\Delta\\_{s}A\\_{s}}\\right)\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{i}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}^{\\top}\\right)\\Delta\\_{i}{\\bm{B}}\\_{i}x\\_{i} | (20) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| =[(∏s=0t𝑹s⊤)​𝑪t]⊤​∑i=0t(∏s=i+1teΔs​As)​(∏s=0i𝑹s⊤)​Δi​𝑩i​xi.\\displaystyle=\\left[\\left(\\prod\\_{s=0}^{t}{\\bm{R}}\\_{s}^{\\top}\\right){\\bm{C}}\\_{t}\\right]^{\\top}\\